<font color="#FF0000">THANK YOU</font><br>
<tt>Wed Oct 29  5:34:10 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Chet,<br>
     I read your post saying you just <br>
wanted someone, to listen and care and recognize the sacrifices that were made. It made me realize how seldom we say what we are feeling to the ones it matters to most.<br>
     Last night, my mother and I were discussing the terrible losses and ongoing tragedies of the Vietnam War (my partner is reexperiencing the horrors on a daily basis).  I was relating to her some of the painful stories he had shared with me, as well as the many that I have read about.  As we got into it she started crying for all of the beautiful idealistic young men who chose to fight for their country and had a part of their souls robbed by that war; and out of rage for the fat old men who sent them off to be slaughtered and stole the youth of the survivors; and for the tragedy of these children coming home to a country that abandoned them and left them to absorb the shame that was ours for having failed to protect them in the first place.  We both cried, knowing that it was finally time to truly mourn the tremendous loss - a memory of a time for which previously we could only bear to feel outrage toward.  I think that most American's who lived through those times are avoiding the subject, because they are only trying to avoid their own shame that our country could allow this to happen, to abandon our men in Vietnam, then abandon them when they got home when they needed our support most of all and now after all of these years there has been so little effort to rectify the damage.  My mother marched against that war, because she saw her own child in the faces of each of those boys. My father, a captain in the Navy and WWII pilot saluted her on the sidelines.  They both knew the true tragedy of war, they were 100% for those boys and 100% against losing them to that war.  I've seen a great deal of controversy on these posts on this subject, but tolerance and understanding will be our greatest ally.  There were zealots on both sides, but mostly we were a bunch of idealistic kids with different ways of seeing the world - life is so black and white when you're young.  I look at the youth and innocence of my young adult children and remember my own - many of you had it stolen from you - no wonder there was so much anger toward the carefree  college boys that you had to face when you got home - it must have felt so unfair. But forgiving ourselves and others is imperative in order for any of us to ever heal.  I was in high school from '68-'71 and my heart bled everytime I saw the lifeless bodies of boys close to my age being dragged across the tv screen (I can never even imagine what you went through first hand).  I was against that war (as a woman, I obviously wasn't a draft dodger), but I have the greatest respect for you men who went over there ready to give your lifes for your country.  If I had it to do over again, I would protest it even more vehemently, but one thing I would do differently is that I would also be organizing rallies to the airport to welcome you home and making a point of thanking every man I saw in uniform for his service - I never had any idea how important that was - I apologize for being one of those who abandoned you.<br>
  There is a depth of spirit that I have never failed to see in every Vietnam Veteran I've met - hard earned - it is now your greatest asset when tempered with tolerance and forgiveness.  A lot of war protesters were called &quot;bleeding hearts&quot; - my experience has been that a lot of those same bleeding hearts are the vet's greatest admirers and defenders today - it's just that everyone seems afraid to bring it up.  My partner's PTSD symptoms have driven everyone away including his flag waving father who encouraged him to join in the first place.  But he just can't seem to get rid of me, I see the incredible man he is under all of the pain.  After witnessing his depth of soul and indominable spirit, other men's lives and love seem trivial, so we persevere one step at a time.  I can't take it away, but I can offer unwaivering arms to hold him.  So from this &quot;bleeding heart&quot; to all of the men who served in Vietnam ...THANK YOU, and I am praying that we will come together as a country to help end the ongoing despair that seems to be affecting so many.  You are still serving our country with your stories - please know that you are honored greatly by so many who simply haven't found the appropriate words to speak.  That war tore this country apart, perhaps we can now use our strength of conviction that led us on different paths, to start rebuilding a common ground of loving support.   
<p><code>-- LS90@webtv.net  (Anne) </code><p>


